00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:56.980
to our shared understanding

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:01.340
of what the revolution
means for our country.

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:05.600
I come 19th Century
Irish background.

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:08.140 position:56%
Not part of the American Revolution,

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.000
and yet the American
Revolution is all of our realm.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.050
I mean, it created our political
system for better or worse.

00:05:15.050 --> 00:05:17.170
I think better some days.

00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:19.450
But there you are.

00:05:19.450 --> 00:05:25.480
The -- my comments today
will be woven someway --

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:28.430
I'm not quite clear, into a book

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:31.880
that I'm writing, I
was researching here.

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:37.460
And it's called <i>An Appeal to
Heaven </i>, which was the major slogan

00:05:37.460 --> 00:05:39.160
of the American revolutionaries,

00:05:39.160 --> 00:05:42.490
certainly in the first
-- 1775 and 6.

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:46.880
So it's <i>An Appeal to Heaven:
The American Revolution </i>.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:51.820
And this book proposes to
address several questions.

00:05:51.820 --> 00:05:54.050
My paper today won't
address all of these,

00:05:54.050 --> 00:05:57.800
but I certainly will
entertain questions.

00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:03.360
One of the oldest questions is
still out there and that is,

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:07.020
what was revolutionary about
the American Revolution?

00:06:07.020 --> 00:06:09.610
At the end of the day
that's still a problem.

00:06:09.610 --> 00:06:12.200
Second, how did ordinary people --

00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:15.020
men and women living in small
communities from Georgia

00:06:15.020 --> 00:06:17.700
to New Hampshire --
experience the revolution?

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:22.380
Not as soldiers, but as members
of small communities sustaining

00:06:22.380 --> 00:06:26.840
and mobilizing, and re-mobilizing
a revolution that succeeded --

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:30.390
in fact, the book will
argue that although most

00:06:30.390 --> 00:06:35.730
of our attention still is on
the great leaders of the time,

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:37.720
and maybe on the battlefields --

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:41.520
like NFL plays, you follow
the little marches around.

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:42.820
It's all important.

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:44.120
I'm not denigrating that.

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:47.260
But if it hadn't been for small
towns that never saw the face

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:52.610 position:56%
of war -- that sustained the
revolution -- we would not have won.

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:55.700
I mean it was the people
who got behind the cause

00:06:55.700 --> 00:06:58.210
and keep the cause alive.

00:06:58.210 --> 00:07:05.010
And third, is a question
that developed in the course

00:07:05.010 --> 00:07:11.930 position:56%
of my research here, and that is how
did a war that generated such hate,

00:07:11.930 --> 00:07:16.160
such bitterness, a sense of
revenge, anger, domestic enemies --

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:21.460
your neighbors could have killed
your family or destroyed your farm.

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:25.170
There was hostility in the
land, and yet at the end

00:07:25.170 --> 00:07:30.080 position:56%
of the American Revolution it ended.

00:07:30.080 --> 00:07:32.700
Unlike almost every other
revolution we can think of,

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:38.710
our revolution stopped and
there was not killing fields

00:07:38.710 --> 00:07:43.440
or massive sense of
revenge in the land.

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:45.510
I think that's something
needs to be explained.

00:07:45.510 --> 00:07:50.720
Not in order to praise us as
an exceptional revolution,

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:53.670
but as a problematic in
comparing our revolution

00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:57.970
with other revolutions
throughout the war.

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:04.780
Like a good undergraduate teacher
I have a crude handout some

00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:07.620
of you have I hope.

00:08:07.620 --> 00:08:11.410
I always praise the crudity
of my handouts because I claim

00:08:11.410 --> 00:08:14.700
that it's more authentic --
its like more revolutionary.

00:08:14.700 --> 00:08:20.330
It was neat, you see, you
wouldn't -- it wouldn't be proper.

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:25.130
So, at the start -- and let me just
read my comments as best I can,

00:08:25.130 --> 00:08:27.390
and welcome your questions.

00:08:27.390 --> 00:08:32.640 position:56%
Let me warn you in advance that
this is a very radical presentation,

00:08:32.640 --> 00:08:35.960
and if you want to leave now
or you're going to be offend --

00:08:35.960 --> 00:08:37.660
it's a triggering moment.

00:08:37.660 --> 00:08:41.860
Right? You're going to
hear some radical things.

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:47.620
Rest assured, I'm not proposing
anything wildly conspiratorial

00:08:47.620 --> 00:08:51.160
such as that George Washington
was really a secret agent

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:55.300
for the British Parliament or
that the founding fathers wanted

00:08:55.300 --> 00:08:59.100
to redistribute land and
property to the peasants

00:08:59.100 --> 00:09:02.100
in the name of worker equality.

00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:05.620
Rather drawing on the research
that I've been pursuing here

00:09:05.620 --> 00:09:08.330
at the center, thanks
to Ted and his friends,

00:09:08.330 --> 00:09:14.720
I want to interrogate closely
a revolutionary narrative

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:16.880
that Americans -- all
of us I think --

00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:23.260
have been telling ourselves about
the nature of the nations origins.

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:28.490
The process of reconsidering the
relationship between chronology

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:32.550
and narrative, between
the assumptions about time

00:09:32.550 --> 00:09:37.360
and its effect on causality
raises for me at least, exciting,

00:09:37.360 --> 00:09:41.320
even radical new questions
about the fundamental character

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:44.730
of the American Revolution.

00:09:44.730 --> 00:09:47.840
Now even to pose the question --

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:50.310
as I have in the title
of the lecture --

00:09:50.310 --> 00:09:53.670
what time was the American
Revolution --

00:09:53.670 --> 00:09:56.290
may strike you as slightly perverse

00:09:56.290 --> 00:10:00.100
since in fact the temporal
boundaries of revolution

00:10:00.100 --> 00:10:03.560
from the initial colonial
grievances to the achievement

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:07.430
of political stability under the
federal constitution have been well

00:10:07.430 --> 00:10:09.840 position:56%
established in the historical memory

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:13.710
of the United States
for several centuries.

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:17.320
But however persuasive
this narrative may be,

00:10:17.320 --> 00:10:23.360
recent and ongoing research
invites a thorough rethinking

00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:26.890
of the familiar account.

00:10:26.890 --> 00:10:30.350
Although some scholars
once traced the origins

00:10:30.350 --> 00:10:34.820
of the American Revolution
back to the dark forrest

00:10:34.820 --> 00:10:37.790
of ancient Germany --
they really did that.

00:10:37.790 --> 00:10:42.560
And others have insisted that the
American Revolution did not realize

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:47.640
its full revolutionary potential
until the age of Jackson.

00:10:47.640 --> 00:10:50.780 position:56%
The story of our national origins --

00:10:50.780 --> 00:10:53.730
think of third grade
again in your life --

00:10:53.730 --> 00:11:00.920
most often begins with the
1760 coronation of George III

00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:05.750
and then step by step it traces
the growth of colonial unrest

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:11.890
from resistance to the Stamp
Act, through the Boston Massacre,

00:11:11.890 --> 00:11:16.790
the Tea Party, the Battle of
Bunker Hill, and then the drafting

00:11:16.790 --> 00:11:19.450
of the Declaration of Independence.

00:11:19.450 --> 00:11:24.250
After this defining moment
in 1776, the standard litany

00:11:24.250 --> 00:11:30.080
of events loses some of its clarity
and many historians have leapt

00:11:30.080 --> 00:11:33.220
with interpretive grace
from the Declaration

00:11:33.220 --> 00:11:36.650
of Independence all the
way to the Constitution.

00:11:36.650 --> 00:11:40.910
I call this the lily pad or
the frog pond theory of leaping

00:11:40.910 --> 00:11:44.430
from one event to another event.

00:11:44.430 --> 00:11:48.740
Of course this traditional approach
of time and narrative works best

00:11:48.740 --> 00:11:52.190
with intellectual history
or the story of history

00:11:52.190 --> 00:11:56.280
of political thought, since the
development of abstract concepts

00:11:56.280 --> 00:12:01.460
such as virtue and liberty
often does not concern itself

00:12:01.460 --> 00:12:04.940
with the changes social
and political context

00:12:04.940 --> 00:12:07.770
of the events on the ground.

00:12:07.770 --> 00:12:12.410
To be sure, a revolutionary
narrative framed by the accession

00:12:12.410 --> 00:12:15.180
of George III and the ratification

00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:20.500
of the Constitution does possess
a kind of compelling logic.

00:12:20.500 --> 00:12:25.260
It allows us to navigate
a smooth interpretive path

00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:30.220
from national liberation
to political stability.

00:12:30.220 --> 00:12:34.640
This traditional periodization
however,

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:37.410
raises a troublesome
interpretive challenge.

00:12:37.410 --> 00:12:42.980
The standard narratives
suggest be it implicitly a kind

00:12:42.980 --> 00:12:47.800
of inevitability of
celebratory chronicle

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:52.800
of the American people marching
forward under the banner of liberty

00:12:52.800 --> 00:12:55.730
and rights to their
well deserved destiny

00:12:55.730 --> 00:12:58.620
as citizens of the New Republic.

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:05.360
Not surprisingly, this complacent
story lends itself to organic,

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:09.060
even providential metaphors.

00:13:09.060 --> 00:13:10.360
You know them.

00:13:10.360 --> 00:13:12.520
Children growing up and demanding

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:16.100
that the mother country
treat them with respect.

00:13:16.100 --> 00:13:21.650 position:56%
Or colonies growing to maturity like
political plants until they flower

00:13:21.650 --> 00:13:25.220
in the form of political
independence.

00:13:25.220 --> 00:13:28.130
From these perspectives,
the temporal flow

00:13:28.130 --> 00:13:31.990
of crucial events acquires
a kind of causal aspect,

00:13:31.990 --> 00:13:36.370
becoming in the telling a
coherent teleological tale

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:39.280 position:56%
in which one thing leads necessarily

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:42.440
to another thing from
beginning to end.

00:13:42.440 --> 00:13:47.370 position:56%
The description of the nations
origins therefore often takes a kind

00:13:47.370 --> 00:13:50.140
of self-congratulatory tone.

00:13:50.140 --> 00:13:54.850
One grounded on the assumption
of American exceptionalism.

00:13:54.850 --> 00:13:58.310
A belief that our revolution,

00:13:58.310 --> 00:14:03.000
this revolution was
somehow different, special.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:04.300
Even unique.

00:14:04.300 --> 00:14:08.500
Unlike other revolutions that
have shaped the modern world.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:12.710
In this rendering there's
not much incentive to engage

00:14:12.710 --> 00:14:14.460
in a comparative analysis.

00:14:14.460 --> 00:14:17.990
In other words, to examine
whether the American revolutionary

00:14:17.990 --> 00:14:23.890
experience over time
paralleled in interesting ways

00:14:23.890 --> 00:14:27.270
that of other nations
throughout the world.

00:14:27.270 --> 00:14:29.080
The French Revolution.

00:14:29.080 --> 00:14:31.080
The Haitian Revolution.

00:14:31.080 --> 00:14:33.540
The Russian Revolution.

00:14:33.540 --> 00:14:37.500
What is at stake in
posing a question

00:14:37.500 --> 00:14:42.330
about revolutionary time therefore,
is the possibility, the invitation,

00:14:42.330 --> 00:14:46.830
the excitement of developing
a less teleological,

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:52.650 position:56%
more coherent understanding of the
relationship between interpretation,

00:14:52.650 --> 00:14:57.230
periodization, and narrative.

00:14:57.230 --> 00:15:03.040
The alternative conceptualization
of revolutionary time that I want

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:10.580
to advance here is that what
we now think of generally

00:15:10.580 --> 00:15:14.200
as the single essentially
monolithic block of time --

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:19.620
a block of time roughly
from 1760 to 1788 --

00:15:19.620 --> 00:15:23.940
should in fact be three
discrete segments.

00:15:23.940 --> 00:15:28.360
Each demanding its own interpretive
standing in the flow of time.

00:15:28.360 --> 00:15:34.360 position:56%
I bring to bear evidence number one.

00:15:34.360 --> 00:15:36.080
You can look, you can follow.

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:41.980
You see the block of
time and now through it.

00:15:41.980 --> 00:15:43.750
It'll be on the final exam.

00:15:43.750 --> 00:15:46.260
So pay attention.

00:15:54.580 --> 00:16:00.090
This revised perspective does
not start with the assumption

00:16:00.090 --> 00:16:04.290
that history is moving
towards a predestined goal

00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:08.340
such as greater democracy,
or more personal freedom,

00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:11.390
or a powerful American empire.

00:16:11.390 --> 00:16:14.630
Rather my argument
begins with the assertion

00:16:14.630 --> 00:16:18.040
that the period most often
associated with the run

00:16:18.040 --> 00:16:21.510
up to the revolution and the
Declaration of Independence --

00:16:21.510 --> 00:16:28.040
in other words, the period 1760 to
1773 -- was nothing of the sort.

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:32.140
These years are more accurately
defined as a general crisis

00:16:32.140 --> 00:16:36.250
of imperial rule throughout
the Atlantic world.

00:16:36.250 --> 00:16:42.610
The relatively minor provincial
risings in the American colony --

00:16:42.610 --> 00:16:47.640 position:56%
the Stamp Act crisis, the Boston
Massacre, the destruction of the tea

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:52.240
in Boston harbor, lets face
it, were really minor tremors

00:16:52.240 --> 00:16:57.630 position:56%
in an ongoing effort by an ambitious
imperial power to make sense

00:16:57.630 --> 00:17:01.550
of the unprecedented
challenge of governing peoples,

00:17:01.550 --> 00:17:05.820 position:56%
of different races, and of different
backgrounds, and of different places

00:17:05.820 --> 00:17:11.080
over a vast world in which
communication remained slow

00:17:11.080 --> 00:17:12.510
and unreliable.

00:17:12.510 --> 00:17:19.210
The second stage -- the second
new stage of this revised version

00:17:19.210 --> 00:17:25.730
of revolutionary time begins in
1774 with the military occupation

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:30.130
of Boston and ends with
the Peace Treaty of 1783.

00:17:30.130 --> 00:17:36.840
A period during which a colonial
rebellion -- colonial rebellion --

00:17:36.840 --> 00:17:42.980
transformed itself into a genuine
political and social revolution.

00:17:42.980 --> 00:17:47.470
It involved the experience of
armed resistance, of large numbers

00:17:47.470 --> 00:17:51.620
of ordinary people suddenly
assuming meaningful authority

00:17:51.620 --> 00:17:54.910
for the first time in
communities throughout American,

00:17:54.910 --> 00:17:59.420
and of social relations that were
no longer defined by monarchy

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:01.930
or aristocratic relationships.

00:18:01.930 --> 00:18:05.780
These developments
promoted a strong sense

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:14.180
of republic equality among
white males that turned itself

00:18:14.180 --> 00:18:21.600 position:56%
into initial armed response against
monarchical authority and eventually

00:18:21.600 --> 00:18:29.260
into a revolution few people
wanted or anticipated in 1776.

00:18:29.260 --> 00:18:32.370
The third period -- again,
look at your chart --

00:18:32.370 --> 00:18:38.100
in this revised narrative is the
years following the end of the war.

00:18:38.100 --> 00:18:42.700
Did not lead inevitably
to the Constitution,

00:18:42.700 --> 00:18:44.650
the federal constitution.

00:18:44.650 --> 00:18:47.520
Divorce from the traditional
triumph discourse --

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:52.920
of which we all know we should
see the period after 1770 --

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:59.500
1783 as a post-revolutionary moment
in which ordinary people came

00:18:59.500 --> 00:19:05.140
to terms with life under an
experimental federal regime

00:19:05.140 --> 00:19:09.440
and as they did so,
they sought to reabsorb

00:19:09.440 --> 00:19:14.830
into an uncertain civil society
a large number of Americans

00:19:14.830 --> 00:19:19.010
who had recently sided
with Great Britain.

00:19:19.010 --> 00:19:24.680
To depict this decade of the
1780's as "the critical period" --

00:19:24.680 --> 00:19:27.880
that's what it's called
in most books --

00:19:27.880 --> 00:19:33.400
it focuses unwarranted attention on
elite fears of disorder and anarchy

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:36.850
and by so doing, turns an explosion

00:19:36.850 --> 00:19:41.610
of entrepreneurial energy
among ordinary men and women

00:19:41.610 --> 00:19:46.360
into an alarming account of a
revolution betrayed at the moment

00:19:46.360 --> 00:19:48.960
of it's greatest success.

00:19:51.530 --> 00:20:00.960
So let me explain a little bit the
rationale for this new narrative.

00:20:00.960 --> 00:20:06.600
And Ted, do you have
a whip or something?

00:20:06.600 --> 00:20:09.640
A prod if I go.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:17.780
A radical recasting of
revolutionary chronology begins

00:20:17.780 --> 00:20:25.590
with a thorough reassessment
of the period before 1775.

00:20:25.590 --> 00:20:29.420
These years seem especially
vulnerable

00:20:29.420 --> 00:20:32.090
to teleological interpretation.

00:20:32.090 --> 00:20:36.920
One can easily understand
the temptation to anticipate

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:41.780
in the years, the coming of
revolution and independence.

00:20:41.780 --> 00:20:46.270
Because we know -- we know what's
coming and it appear only fair

00:20:46.270 --> 00:20:53.550
from this perspective to depict
every event as a harbinger

00:20:53.550 --> 00:20:57.320
to the final break with
Great Britain, but even armed

00:20:57.320 --> 00:21:01.580
with the clarity of hindsight
there's no reason to conclude

00:21:01.580 --> 00:21:06.780
that local complaints about
imperial rule, even urban riots,

00:21:06.780 --> 00:21:13.460
even threats of organized
resistance amounted to any more

00:21:13.460 --> 00:21:19.070
than what they were, highly limited
protests that lost the potential

00:21:19.070 --> 00:21:22.720
for a large scale mobilization
within days or months

00:21:22.720 --> 00:21:24.740
of their initial occurrence.

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:28.800
Such episodes hardly
represented a serious break

00:21:28.800 --> 00:21:30.470
with imperial authority.

00:21:30.470 --> 00:21:35.710
Throughout the 18th Century the
British showed remarkable ability

00:21:35.710 --> 00:21:41.530
to maintain order in
England, Scotland, Ireland.

00:21:41.530 --> 00:21:47.130 position:56%
The negotiations in this empire
usually involved a pragmatic mixture

00:21:47.130 --> 00:21:49.830
or carrots and sticks, and
at the end of the day even

00:21:49.830 --> 00:21:52.480
when lethal violence was employed,

00:21:52.480 --> 00:21:57.160
the narrative process successfully
re-channeled local anger.

00:21:57.160 --> 00:22:02.710 position:56%
For example, the bloody conclusion
of the Massacre at St. George Fields

00:22:02.710 --> 00:22:06.080
in London in a tense 1768.

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:09.360
There were at least seven people
brought down by government troops.

00:22:09.360 --> 00:22:12.640
About the same as the
Boston Massacre.

00:22:12.640 --> 00:22:17.790
But this was not a sign that the
British people were conspiring

00:22:17.790 --> 00:22:20.520
to launch a revolution?

00:22:20.520 --> 00:22:23.440
Conditions in North American
colonies were not that .

00:22:23.440 --> 00:22:29.530
The Boston Massacre certainly did
not lead inevitably to Bunker Hill

00:22:29.530 --> 00:22:31.140
or the Declaration of Independence.

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:36.300
Instead, the event introduced
three years of extraordinary peace.

00:22:36.300 --> 00:22:41.930
1770 to 1773 were the most
peaceful, consumer oriented years

00:22:41.930 --> 00:22:44.050
of the whole colonial period.

00:22:44.050 --> 00:22:49.020
And poor Sam Adams was in
utter despair in his ability

00:22:49.020 --> 00:22:52.160
to persuade the people that
they had legitimate grievances

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:53.460
against the empire.

00:22:53.460 --> 00:23:00.390
No doubt, Parliament's
attempts during the 1760's

00:23:00.390 --> 00:23:06.410
to raise revenue -- stamps, sugar,
tea -- irritated the Americans,

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:10.210
especially those that
lived in the port cities.

00:23:10.210 --> 00:23:15.550
But, the fact of the matter is
that those Boston agitators even

00:23:15.550 --> 00:23:20.400
at the height of the Stamp Act
crisis did not receive much support

00:23:20.400 --> 00:23:23.630
from the ordinary people
living in other parts

00:23:23.630 --> 00:23:26.590
of the British American colonies.

00:23:26.590 --> 00:23:29.030
Leaders of the colonial
assemblies wrote

00:23:29.030 --> 00:23:32.980
to other leaders of
colonial assemblies.

00:23:32.980 --> 00:23:36.630 position:56%
They talked about possible coercion,

00:23:36.630 --> 00:23:41.100
about making stamp collectors
resign, but that was about it.

00:23:41.100 --> 00:23:44.820
Even in Massachusetts town meetings

00:23:44.820 --> 00:23:47.850
in the countryside
showed little enthusiasm

00:23:47.850 --> 00:23:51.570
for an agenda of the
Boston radicals.

00:23:51.570 --> 00:23:55.030
And I can say I've gone through all
the town records and they're still

00:23:55.030 --> 00:23:57.740
in print of these towns
of Massachusetts,

00:23:57.740 --> 00:24:02.730
and outside of Boston there was a
big yawn about what those wackos

00:24:02.730 --> 00:24:07.020
in Boston were up to in 1765.

00:24:07.020 --> 00:24:13.780
So the ability to limit and control
occasional controversy is precisely

00:24:13.780 --> 00:24:16.630
what one would have
expected at the time.

00:24:16.630 --> 00:24:18.460
Even if there had been
no revolution.

00:24:18.460 --> 00:24:22.770
After all, the American colonists
viewed the victory over the French

00:24:22.770 --> 00:24:27.170
in the Seven Years War as
incontrovertible evidence

00:24:27.170 --> 00:24:30.470
of their American loyalty
to the empire.

00:24:30.470 --> 00:24:33.190
And by their own lives,
they were not full partners

00:24:33.190 --> 00:24:36.290
in a powerful expanding
imperial regime.

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:39.910
In so much, as the Americans
experienced a growing sense

00:24:39.910 --> 00:24:45.730
of nationalism after the
war, the expressed it

00:24:45.730 --> 00:24:52.420
in almost a reflective emotional
attachment to Great Britain.

00:24:52.420 --> 00:24:57.160
Indeed, many historians call
this phenomena I think rightly,

00:24:57.160 --> 00:25:00.120
the sense of colonial nationalism.

00:25:00.120 --> 00:25:07.570
What then, you might say -- should
there be any critics out there --

00:25:07.570 --> 00:25:13.630
of the much quoted pamphlets
that drive the standard account

00:25:13.630 --> 00:25:17.530
of the American -- the
coming of the revolution?

00:25:17.530 --> 00:25:20.860
Surely like the prophets
of the Old Testament,

00:25:20.860 --> 00:25:23.600
they were preparing the way.

00:25:23.600 --> 00:25:27.330
But in fact, celebrated
writers such as John Adams

00:25:27.330 --> 00:25:33.070
and John Dickinson were not
harolds of an independent republic.

00:25:33.070 --> 00:25:38.850
The colonists who analyzed the
American grievances were members

00:25:38.850 --> 00:25:40.260
of a creole elite.

00:25:40.260 --> 00:25:45.170
In other words, a group of wealthy,
privileged, well-educated men

00:25:45.170 --> 00:25:51.040
who felt themselves marginalized
within the imperial structure.

00:25:51.040 --> 00:25:54.170
That was their problem.

00:25:54.170 --> 00:25:58.130
Not enough patronage
is going our way.

00:25:58.130 --> 00:26:00.780
What these ambitious
Americans wanted was --

00:26:00.780 --> 00:26:04.360
lets put it bluntly -- respect.

00:26:04.360 --> 00:26:08.200
To be accepted by the leading
British political figures

00:26:08.200 --> 00:26:10.960
as fully British and
not as lesser beings

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:16.010
who inhabited the marshlands
of empire.

00:26:16.010 --> 00:26:21.580
George Washington sulked when he
was not given a proper commission

00:26:21.580 --> 00:26:23.240
in the British Army.

00:26:23.240 --> 00:26:26.550
John Adams looking to
make a political --

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:30.380
or legal career in
Massachusetts complained bitterly

00:26:30.380 --> 00:26:35.220
that Hutchison's clan
got all the business,

00:26:35.220 --> 00:26:38.510
and he had not received
any imperial patronage.

00:26:38.510 --> 00:26:44.510
Protesting his imagined inferiority
in British eyes, Adams announced,

00:26:44.510 --> 00:26:50.630
I say we are as handsome
as English folks here

00:26:50.630 --> 00:26:53.520
and therefore should be free.

00:26:53.520 --> 00:26:54.880
James Otis agreed.

00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:57.970
Benjamin Franklin held out
in the hope of acceptance

00:26:57.970 --> 00:26:59.960
to the very eve of revolution.

00:26:59.960 --> 00:27:04.250
It was only when he was humiliated
during a public hearing in London

00:27:04.250 --> 00:27:09.560
that he finally decided that
Philadelphia was his home.

00:27:12.410 --> 00:27:15.640
Creole leaders were not
plotting revolution.

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:20.220
They only wanted to be
accepted in the imperial club.

00:27:20.220 --> 00:27:22.760
Frances Bernard -- a royal governor

00:27:22.760 --> 00:27:25.000
of Massachusetts during
the 1760's --

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:27.210
a very smart and misunderstood
man --

00:27:27.210 --> 00:27:32.520
understood how to accommodate
these upity colonials.

00:27:32.520 --> 00:27:36.530
And he advised the Earl
of Hillsborough in 1769

00:27:36.530 --> 00:27:41.540
that if Parliament would only
create a kind of upper house

00:27:41.540 --> 00:27:45.220
in each colony, a kind of
American House of Lords filled

00:27:45.220 --> 00:27:49.280
with wealthy Americans appointed
by the King, it would --

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:53.670
and I quote Bernard -- go a
long way to remedy the disorders

00:27:53.670 --> 00:27:57.000
to which the government
of America is subject to.

00:27:57.000 --> 00:28:00.280
And he predicted --
I think correctly --

00:28:00.280 --> 00:28:04.130
that eager Americans would fall
all over themselves to have --

00:28:04.130 --> 00:28:09.040
and I quote again -- Barron
prefixed to their name.

00:28:09.040 --> 00:28:11.980
The beauty of the change
would be that in the addition

00:28:11.980 --> 00:28:17.630
of so many royal honors from the
new form of govern, it will assist

00:28:17.630 --> 00:28:24.020 position:56%
in the establishment of it by
engaging men who are ripe for honors

00:28:24.020 --> 00:28:26.660
to reconciling the
people to the system

00:28:26.660 --> 00:28:30.950
that introduces the new honors.

00:28:30.950 --> 00:28:33.470
Nothing came with the plan.

00:28:33.470 --> 00:28:38.330
Since in fact parliamentary leaders
did look at the Americans as well

00:28:38.330 --> 00:28:42.340
as the Irish, as well as the
Scots, as inferior subjects.

00:28:42.340 --> 00:28:45.530
That's true.

00:28:45.530 --> 00:28:50.820
But bias here threatened what
could have been a brilliant reform

00:28:50.820 --> 00:28:53.120
to save the empire.

00:28:55.030 --> 00:28:59.650
What once appeared as
simply the inevitable run

00:28:59.650 --> 00:29:01.690
up to the American
Revolution therefore takes

00:29:01.690 --> 00:29:05.470
on a very different
character when we view it

00:29:05.470 --> 00:29:09.650
as a crisis within the empire.

00:29:09.650 --> 00:29:12.430
Great Britain was not
alone in having troubles

00:29:12.430 --> 00:29:15.120
with demanding creole leaders.

00:29:15.120 --> 00:29:18.010
Throughout the new world
they demanded more authority.

00:29:18.010 --> 00:29:21.690
They demanded a meaningful
voice in the Atlantic economy.

00:29:21.690 --> 00:29:24.790
This was the moment when
the British, the French,

00:29:24.790 --> 00:29:28.160
and the Spanish discovered for the
first time that they were not fully

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:32.480
in control of the lands and
the peoples of the new world

00:29:32.480 --> 00:29:35.290
that they claimed to rule.

00:29:35.290 --> 00:29:39.220
The new world remained
uncharted territory

00:29:39.220 --> 00:29:42.340
for these imperial administrators.

00:29:42.340 --> 00:29:48.040
And awareness of this demanding,
fluent, fluid experimental aspect

00:29:48.040 --> 00:29:53.450
of 18th Century expansion I think
erodes our standard revolutionary

00:29:53.450 --> 00:29:55.500
narrative and indeed it brings us

00:29:55.500 --> 00:30:03.390
into an unprecedented
imperial crisis.

00:30:03.390 --> 00:30:08.900
And reminds us that the
pre-revolutionary period was not

00:30:08.900 --> 00:30:11.660
pre-revolutionary at all.

00:30:11.660 --> 00:30:17.110
It was rather a period of sorting
out complex relations, races,

00:30:17.110 --> 00:30:21.800
distances, peoples
throughout a territory

00:30:21.800 --> 00:30:24.690
that amounted to half the globe.

00:30:28.170 --> 00:30:30.960
The second, even more
significant break

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:34.760
in the standard revolutionary
time in 1774.

00:30:34.760 --> 00:30:36.530
This was a crucial year.

00:30:36.530 --> 00:30:41.690
This was the major year that
witnessed the rendering of time,

00:30:41.690 --> 00:30:46.730
rendering of the old narrative
we all learned in third grade.

00:30:46.730 --> 00:30:50.890
For although memories of an
earlier period shaped the political

00:30:50.890 --> 00:30:55.510
consensus of consciousness
of Americans the landscape

00:30:55.510 --> 00:31:00.100
of power underwent a
sudden and profound shift.

00:31:00.100 --> 00:31:05.460
And the trigger for massive change
was not the traditional story

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:11.200
of the coming of the American
Revolution, the Boston Tea Party.

00:31:11.200 --> 00:31:13.440
It was not the Boston Tea Party.

00:31:13.440 --> 00:31:18.810
Many Americans saw the destruction
of the private property in Boston

00:31:18.810 --> 00:31:22.590
as an extreme and unpleasant
form of protest.

00:31:22.590 --> 00:31:24.980
As an unwarranted provocation.

00:31:24.980 --> 00:31:27.320
An attack on property.

00:31:27.320 --> 00:31:31.940
And there was in fact almost no
outpouring of popular support

00:31:31.940 --> 00:31:33.240
for the people of Boston

00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:35.690
who organized throwing
the tea into the water.

00:31:35.690 --> 00:31:43.660
What fundamentally and irrevocably
transformed the character

00:31:43.660 --> 00:31:48.090
of colonial politics was not
the destruction of the tea,

00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:52.590
but the reaction in Parliament
to the destruction of the tea.

00:31:52.590 --> 00:31:57.510
The story of protest by creole
leaders suddenly became a tale

00:31:57.510 --> 00:32:02.090
of massive popular mobilization.

00:32:02.090 --> 00:32:09.330
And so in 1774 we enter an entirely
new, unprecedented political world.

00:32:09.330 --> 00:32:12.160
Lord North and his
allies passed a series

00:32:12.160 --> 00:32:16.500
of harsh retaliatory acts
known as the Coercive Acts,

00:32:16.500 --> 00:32:20.440
which not only closed the Port
of Boston to all commerce,

00:32:20.440 --> 00:32:24.430
but more important -- and
I think we overlook --

00:32:24.430 --> 00:32:29.990 position:56%
authorized armed military occupation

00:32:29.990 --> 00:32:34.620
of the second largest
city in colonial America.

00:32:34.620 --> 00:32:38.590
I might say that the Brits had
never used armed occupation

00:32:38.590 --> 00:32:40.610
in their own cities under --

00:32:40.610 --> 00:32:46.270
this was a provocation of
great, great magnitude.

00:32:46.270 --> 00:32:48.860
And for the colonists
living is distant places

00:32:48.860 --> 00:32:51.260 position:56%
such as South Carolina and Virginia,

00:32:51.260 --> 00:32:55.210
the British punishments seemed
totally out of proportion

00:32:55.210 --> 00:32:57.990
with the seriousness of the crime.

00:32:57.990 --> 00:33:03.190
Over night, British -- over night
Boston became a city occupied

00:33:03.190 --> 00:33:08.620
by a standing army and it's
subjects subject to marshal law.

00:33:08.620 --> 00:33:15.930
And suddenly in that year, you find
Americans -- ordinary Americans,

00:33:15.930 --> 00:33:21.200 position:56%
men and women -- talking about
something called the American cause.

00:33:21.200 --> 00:33:26.710
A new phrase in the
lexicon of protest.

00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:31.590
The revisionary view
of revolutionary time

00:33:31.590 --> 00:33:37.090
that I'm proposing takes our
attention away from the writings

00:33:37.090 --> 00:33:39.340
of celebrated leaders, the ones --

00:33:39.340 --> 00:33:44.100
the pamphlets, the arguments
of lawyers and planters.

00:33:44.100 --> 00:33:50.070
My time restores the people who
actually showed up at Bunker Hill

00:33:50.070 --> 00:33:53.870
and figured out what revolution
meant in their lives without having

00:33:53.870 --> 00:33:57.520
to read the learned pamphlets
that figure so centrally

00:33:57.520 --> 00:33:59.970
in our intellectual history.

00:34:06.170 --> 00:34:11.400
One detail -- and I know there's
an Irishman way back there --

00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:16.770 position:56%
one detail I just want to give you
that shall we say, puts on the alert

00:34:16.770 --> 00:34:20.310
about the standard
teleological account, my research

00:34:20.310 --> 00:34:25.130 position:56%
and the research of other scholars
have shown there was a massive flood

00:34:25.130 --> 00:34:27.900
of Irish immigrants -- massive --

00:34:27.900 --> 00:34:32.900
in 1774, 75, into the
American colonies.

00:34:32.900 --> 00:34:37.110
They were driven out of Ireland
-- mostly in the North --

00:34:37.110 --> 00:34:42.020 position:56%
by British restrictions on the linen
industry that were very similar

00:34:42.020 --> 00:34:47.650
to the restrictions on
American stamps and so on.

00:34:47.650 --> 00:34:54.910
My point was, these Irishmen came
to America and had no experience

00:34:54.910 --> 00:34:58.930
or memory of the American
protest of the 1760's.

00:34:58.930 --> 00:35:02.520
They were irritated -- they
knew to hate Brits on their own.

00:35:02.520 --> 00:35:07.390
They didn't need the
American experience.

00:35:07.390 --> 00:35:09.070
So what does it matter?

00:35:09.070 --> 00:35:12.000
Research has found that in
some of the continental lines

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:15.650 position:56%
in Pennsylvania especially, over 60%

00:35:15.650 --> 00:35:21.370
of all the fighting men
were new Irish immigrants.

00:35:21.370 --> 00:35:26.830
Hm-mm, so much for the teleological
argument about growing protests.

00:35:26.830 --> 00:35:32.470
It's the new men, angry
at the empire.

00:35:32.470 --> 00:35:36.950
Now 1775, these protests

00:35:36.950 --> 00:35:42.420
or this resistance did not signal
the start of a genuine revolution.

00:35:42.420 --> 00:35:43.720
That came later.

00:35:43.720 --> 00:35:46.930
At first, most American's
hoped that Lord North

00:35:46.930 --> 00:35:51.430
and his supporters would simply
come to their senses and find a way

00:35:51.430 --> 00:35:55.300
to negotiate a way
to save the empire.

00:35:55.300 --> 00:35:59.190
They wanted reform,
not independence.

00:35:59.190 --> 00:36:02.630
And there was little
-- almost no enthusiasm

00:36:02.630 --> 00:36:04.640
for Republican government.

00:36:04.640 --> 00:36:10.370
From this perspective almost
all Americans in 1776 --

00:36:10.370 --> 00:36:13.040
75 I would say -- were loyalists.

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:14.340
All of them.

00:36:14.340 --> 00:36:16.930
They simply wanted the
British to back down

00:36:16.930 --> 00:36:20.530
and restore an imperial system
that would bring them security

00:36:20.530 --> 00:36:23.680
and respect within the empire.

00:36:23.680 --> 00:36:27.420
Thomas Jefferson noted in
something that you all should read,

00:36:27.420 --> 00:36:29.770
because its kind of
a weird document,

00:36:29.770 --> 00:36:34.630
and that is the first draft of
the Declaration of Independence.

00:36:34.630 --> 00:36:38.020
It's a testimony to good teaching.

00:36:38.020 --> 00:36:40.930
I mean, we all think
it's so well written,

00:36:40.930 --> 00:36:44.840
but it's took his colleagues
to cut the adverbs

00:36:44.840 --> 00:36:48.690
and the adjectives out
and make it pretty.

00:36:48.690 --> 00:36:57.170
What did he write at this moment
of the second period of time?

00:36:57.170 --> 00:37:04.010 position:56%
We might have been a free and great
people together, but a communication

00:37:04.010 --> 00:37:09.850
of grandeur and of freedom it
seems is below the British dignity.

00:37:09.850 --> 00:37:14.530
In so, so they will have
it so, the road to glory

00:37:14.530 --> 00:37:17.010
and happiness is open to us.

00:37:17.010 --> 00:37:21.410 position:56%
We will climb it as a separate
state and acquiesce in the necessity

00:37:21.410 --> 00:37:26.350
which pronounces us to say to
Britain, an everlasting ado.

00:37:26.350 --> 00:37:29.020
That got cut out.

00:37:29.020 --> 00:37:34.780
At the start of the war, therefore
the American insurgence clashed

00:37:34.780 --> 00:37:39.150
over strategies of
reconciliation and not

00:37:39.150 --> 00:37:42.260
over fundamental political ideas.

00:37:42.260 --> 00:37:45.590
Even colonial leaders who later
opposed independence [inaudible]

00:37:45.590 --> 00:37:51.740
at the beginning of resistance
values such as virtue and liberty.

00:37:51.740 --> 00:37:59.150
By 1776, our protest against the
British oppression had begun --

00:37:59.150 --> 00:38:04.490
that had begun as a colonial
rebellion comparative to India

00:38:04.490 --> 00:38:07.920
or Nigeria, or other
former colonial states.

00:38:07.920 --> 00:38:11.410
It had become a real revolution.

00:38:11.410 --> 00:38:14.260
The transformation did
not involve the shift

00:38:14.260 --> 00:38:16.980 position:56%
in fundamental political principles.

00:38:16.980 --> 00:38:21.490
Ideology did not turn
rebellion into revolution.

00:38:21.490 --> 00:38:25.950
After all, the idea that the people
are the only legitimate source

00:38:25.950 --> 00:38:30.200
of political power has a very
long history reaching back

00:38:30.200 --> 00:38:32.500
into the Middle Ages.

00:38:33.530 --> 00:38:39.030 position:56%
The new element in the time equation
was experienced quite simply

00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:42.370
by living through a time of
violent political change.

00:38:42.370 --> 00:38:45.900
It was one -- it's one thing
to discuss with your friends

00:38:45.900 --> 00:38:49.700
in the pub rights and equality in
the abstract, but quite another

00:38:49.700 --> 00:38:57.220
to experience newly formed groups,
army groups, committees of safety

00:38:57.220 --> 00:39:00.380
and inspection that recruited
people that had never served

00:39:00.380 --> 00:39:04.040
in any political movement at all.

00:39:04.040 --> 00:39:09.190
Participation in political
resistance created fresh and new

00:39:09.190 --> 00:39:13.940
and exciting emotional bonds
that carried radical potential.

00:39:13.940 --> 00:39:21.390 position:56%
White American males came to believe
in a crude sense their equality.

00:39:21.390 --> 00:39:25.210
Aristocratic claims to special
privilege no longer counted

00:39:25.210 --> 00:39:26.510
for much.

00:39:26.510 --> 00:39:31.560
Achievement through works
suddenly transcended the old order.

00:39:31.560 --> 00:39:35.420
That's revolutionary in
the late-18th Century.

00:39:36.930 --> 00:39:42.930
To be sure, the language of rights
inspired American revolutionaries.

00:39:42.930 --> 00:39:47.670
The traditional story of
revolution stresses the centrality

00:39:47.670 --> 00:39:52.390
of these enabling principles they
did yesterday in Philadelphia.

00:39:52.390 --> 00:39:55.770
But that approach discounts
other binding elements,

00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:58.610
some of which make
modern commentators

00:39:58.610 --> 00:40:03.270
on our revolution uncomfortable.

00:40:03.270 --> 00:40:11.280
The actual experience of war
included not only Republican ideas,

00:40:11.280 --> 00:40:17.810
but also a forgotten lexicon of
unsettled words such as fear,

00:40:17.810 --> 00:40:20.470
vengeance, retaliation,
denunciation,

00:40:20.470 --> 00:40:22.540
betrayal, revenge, and violence.

00:40:22.540 --> 00:40:26.570
That's part of our revolution too.

00:40:26.570 --> 00:40:31.420
It is this emotionally
charged political environment

00:40:31.420 --> 00:40:34.440
that has gone missing from
the historical literature,

00:40:34.440 --> 00:40:38.680
securing the revolution -- securing
our revolution was difficult

00:40:38.680 --> 00:40:41.490
and dangerous for all people.

00:40:41.490 --> 00:40:45.170
Suspicion of neighbors, enforcing
the revolutionary agenda,

00:40:45.170 --> 00:40:50.080
taking property from domestic
enemies, is often thought as a part

00:40:50.080 --> 00:40:53.410
of the story of other revolutions.

00:40:53.410 --> 00:40:56.000
Less nice, less good
revolutions than ours.

00:40:56.000 --> 00:41:02.660
But I can assure you it was a
nasty business those eight years.

00:41:02.660 --> 00:41:06.910
After the victory of Yorktown,
Americans entered the third

00:41:06.910 --> 00:41:11.840
and final, and blessedly
for you, short period.

00:41:11.840 --> 00:41:18.010
Which is best described I think
as our post-revolutionary period.

00:41:18.010 --> 00:41:23.350
This different terminology
post-revolutionary,

00:41:23.350 --> 00:41:29.210 position:56%
deflects our attention away from the
absolute obsession with the coming

00:41:29.210 --> 00:41:33.500
and the drafting of
the Constitution.

00:41:33.500 --> 00:41:38.020
George Washington, Andrew
Hamilton, James Madison,

00:41:38.020 --> 00:41:40.490
the dominant characters
in the campaign

00:41:40.490 --> 00:41:42.840
to establish a strong
central government --

00:41:42.840 --> 00:41:48.430
certainly they did worry about the
dangers of political fragmentation.

00:41:48.430 --> 00:41:53.200
They became so anxious about the
threat of stability that in fact

00:41:53.200 --> 00:41:59.710 position:56%
that they greatly exaggerated the
danger posed by small agrarian riots

00:41:59.710 --> 00:42:04.600
such as Daniel Shays -- a
group of impoverished veterans

00:42:04.600 --> 00:42:08.130
in Massachusetts that presents
absolutely no military threat

00:42:08.130 --> 00:42:11.680
to anybody, but it
became a national incident

00:42:11.680 --> 00:42:18.630
of great historical power
in our story of stealth.

00:42:18.630 --> 00:42:20.150
But however we may
admire [inaudible],

00:42:20.150 --> 00:42:25.720
we do not have to accept
this analysis.

00:42:25.720 --> 00:42:31.000
If one concentrates chiefly on
elite fears, on looming anarchy

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:33.870
as most American historians
have done,

00:42:33.870 --> 00:42:37.540
one discounts the buoyant optimism

00:42:37.540 --> 00:42:40.850
that characterized the
American people as whole.

00:42:40.850 --> 00:42:45.170
There's not much evidence that
they were paralyzed by anxiety

00:42:45.170 --> 00:42:46.540
over the country's future.

00:42:46.540 --> 00:42:51.530
The revolution in itself
unleashed an extraordinary burst

00:42:51.530 --> 00:42:54.620
of energy and optimism.

00:42:54.620 --> 00:42:58.370
Suddenly after years of
British economic regulation,

00:42:58.370 --> 00:43:02.940
ordinary Americans devised schemes
everywhere to better their lives.

00:43:02.940 --> 00:43:06.400
Build a canal, speculate
on land, a new mill,

00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:11.660
new people were participating
in fresh and exciting,

00:43:11.660 --> 00:43:15.150
and free ways in a growing economy.

00:43:15.150 --> 00:43:17.810 position:56%
And they moved west in huge numbers.

00:43:17.810 --> 00:43:20.020
Probably the worst
thing that ever happened

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:22.710
to the Native American
people's on this continent.

00:43:22.710 --> 00:43:24.010
But they did.

00:43:24.010 --> 00:43:25.310
Like locusts they moved west

00:43:25.310 --> 00:43:28.590
and started new lives
and took up new farms.

00:43:28.590 --> 00:43:33.650
And they had lots and
lots of children.

00:43:33.650 --> 00:43:37.330
The greatest percentage of
population growth in the history

00:43:37.330 --> 00:43:40.810
of the United States
occurred in the 1780's

00:43:40.810 --> 00:43:47.190
and it is almost not traceable to
migration from foreign country.

00:43:47.190 --> 00:43:52.050
Men and women are having kids
because they're optimistic

00:43:52.050 --> 00:43:54.380
about the future of their country.

00:43:54.380 --> 00:43:57.130
They are not sitting around saying,

00:43:57.130 --> 00:44:00.890
oh we need a strong
federal government.

00:44:00.890 --> 00:44:03.070
Where's the -- where should we go?

00:44:03.070 --> 00:44:06.120
To Philadelphia?

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:09.750
The rejection of the
standard narrative,

00:44:09.750 --> 00:44:14.600
a smooth almost predestined tale of
gifted leaders guiding the people

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:18.830
from colonial protest to political
stability, therefore brings

00:44:18.830 --> 00:44:24.240
into fresh focus and new
challenging concerns.

00:44:24.240 --> 00:44:27.520 position:56%
And to me, the payoff seems obvious.

00:44:27.520 --> 00:44:31.040
First, the years before
1774 become part

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:34.220
of a genuinely imperative
world story

00:44:34.220 --> 00:44:37.940
about imperial rivalries
throughout the Atlantic world.

00:44:37.940 --> 00:44:40.420
The competition for military

00:44:40.420 --> 00:44:44.170
and commercial dominance shaped
the lives of ordinary Europeans

00:44:44.170 --> 00:44:47.930
and African slaves, as well
as indigenous people's.

00:44:47.930 --> 00:44:52.730
Second, an account of the
actual experience of living

00:44:52.730 --> 00:44:56.140
through a revolution
restores ordinary people

00:44:56.140 --> 00:45:00.500
to a tale previously dominated
by a group of leaders.

00:45:00.500 --> 00:45:03.680
It liberates us from the
obsession on the founding fathers

00:45:03.680 --> 00:45:08.970
and gives genuine agency to
the people in the creation

00:45:08.970 --> 00:45:11.760
of their own new republic.

00:45:11.760 --> 00:45:15.510
And third, by rejecting
the teleological account

00:45:15.510 --> 00:45:20.700
of the Constitution as
almost providential,

00:45:21.850 --> 00:45:28.110 position:56%
restores our appreciation of a surge
of popular entrepreneurial energy

00:45:28.110 --> 00:45:33.260
that generated excitement in
a post-revolutionary society.

00:45:33.260 --> 00:45:38.280
The new periodization of
revolution -- here I pause it --

00:45:38.280 --> 00:45:44.620
is dynamic, its open to the people
who did not pen founding documents

00:45:44.620 --> 00:45:47.650
or serve as generals or statesmen.

00:45:47.650 --> 00:45:53.730
And so, in a surge for a
more textured, more complex,

00:45:53.730 --> 00:45:59.300
more inclusive, more
comparative revolution it is time

00:45:59.300 --> 00:46:06.510
that we all ask ourselves, what
time was the American Revolution?

00:46:06.510 --> 00:46:25.040
